l\n|\nPray for change in your heart and not your circumstance, and you will see what will happen.\n\n- Unarine\n|\nI have lived a long life and had many troubles, most of which never happened\n\n- Mark\n|\nsalvation is for the feeble, that's what I think. I don't want salvation, I want life, all of life, the miserable as well as the superb.\n\n- Tom Robbins, Jitterbug Perfume\n|\nNow I am writing this diary in English, which for me is not the language of intimacy or love, but an attempt at distance and sanity, a means of recalling normality.\n\n- Jasmina Tešanović, The Diary of a Political Idiot: Normal Life in Belgrade\n|\nRequiring neither wood nor urns,Inside me is a fire that burns;Advising me to never accept defeat,The blessed fruit of hope it churns!\n\n- Neelam\n|\nThe future is uncertain, but that can be a good thing.\n\n- Jennifer Niven, All the Bright Places\n|\nIt’s not a big deal to fall madly in love with someone bright, extraordinary and charismatic; a big deal is to become the matching person, who is worthy to be loved back.\n\n- Sahara Sanders, Win the Heart of A Woman of Your Dreams\n|\nBut it is a writer's duty to write and speak and record the truth, always the truth, no matter whom may be offended.\n\n- Edward Abbey, Postcards from Ed: Dispatches and Salvos from an American Iconoclast\n|\nWhoever is first in the field and awaits the coming of the enemy, will be fresh for the fight; whoever is second in the field and has to hasten to battle will arrive exhausted.\n\n- Sun Tzu, The Art of War\n|\nWe cry coming into the world, as everyone around us laughs with joy. And we laugh with joy leaving this world, when everyone around us cries.\n\n- Wendy Corsi Staub, Awakening\n|\nI would so hate to be a first-person character! Always on your guard, always having people read your thoughts!\n\n- Jasper Fforde, Lost in a Good Book\n|\nI am for freedom of religion, and against all maneuvers to bring about a legal ascendency of one sect over another.\n\n- Thom